AB  - Global climate change will continue to expose more communities to drought, a prominent environmental health hazard. Droughts directly and indirectly affect the health of communities through reduced air and water quality, increased incidence of infectious disease, malnutrition, and mental illness. The Po River Basin region in Europe and the Colorado River Basin region in the U.S. illustrate how geography and policy affect the prevalence of health-related consequences of drought. Our study quantifies the relevant health-related consequences of drought in these two regions and identifies the most salient public health challenge in each region. The most salient risk in the Po River Basin is the heavy industry and natural geography that result in poor air quality. In the Colorado River Basin, the emerging disease coccidioidomycosis (Valley fever) poses the most salient risk. By identifying these prominent health-related consequences, public health practitioners and policymakers can more strategically target interventions and policies to reduce the health burden of drought.
