AB  - We investigated the association between daily emergency ambulance calls (EAC) for elevated blood pressure that occurred during the time intervals of 8:00–13:59, 14:00–21:59, and 22:00–7:59, and exposure to CO, PM10, and ozone. We used Poisson regression to explore the association between the risk of EAC and short-term variation of pollutants, adjusting for seasonality and weather variables. Before noon, the risk was associated with an interquartile range (IQR) (7.9 μg/m3) increase in PM10at lag 2–4 days below the median (RR = 1.08,p = 0.031) and with an IQR (0.146 mg/m3) increase in CO at lag 6–7 below the median (RR = 1.05,p = 0.028). During 14:00–21:59, the risk was associated with an IQR (18.8 μg/m3) increase in PM10on the previous day below the median (RR = 1.04,p = 0.031). At night, EAC were negatively affected by lower O3(lag 0–2) below the median (per IQR decrease RR = 1.10,p = 0.018) and a higher PM10at lag 0–1 above the median for the elderly (RR = 1.07,p = 0.030).
