AB  - The article focuses on the barriers and facilitators to accessing sexual health services among asylum seekers in Cork and Kerry, aiming to inform future policies and service provision. A qualitative study involving 14 semi-structured interviews revealed varying levels of understanding of sexual health among participants and identified socioeconomic, political/legal, systemic, and social/cultural/religious factors affecting access to services. The findings emphasize the need for improved information and services to promote public health among asylum seekers. Additionally, the article discusses reproductive health service usage among Roma women in Romania, highlighting significant inequalities in access to prenatal care and cervical cancer screening compared to the general population, and calls for culturally adapted public health policies.
