AB  - Health and AL tend to be positively correlated, but findings are limited because AL is typically assigned solely using personal factors without consideration of AL-related environmental factors. Thus, Hispanic mothers were grouped by AL using a combination of personal (i.e„ survey language, language at home, birth country) and environmental (i.e„ % immigrants and % speaking English less than very well in the neighborhood) factors. Using 5-point scales, ANOVA with Tulcey post-hoc tests revealed home environments differed significantly (p<0.01). Low-AL mothers (n=45) had less indoor/home (3.00±1.01SD vs. 3.39±0.80SD) and neighborhood (3.61±1.05SD vs. 4.12±0.99SD) physical activity space/supports than White mothers (n=340). Low-AL mothers also reported fewer outdoor/yard (3.87±0.92SD vs. 4.58±0.44SD and 4.45±0.59SD) physical activity space/supports and less safe neighborhoods (2.88±0.85SD vs. 3.66±0.73SD and 3.50±0.85SD) than high-AL (n=26) and White mothers. Home media environments were similar; media devices were not easily accessed by children (2.43±1.18SD) and children's bedrooms had few devices (1.28±1.61SD devices). Family mealtime environments differed; low-AL mothers had fewer total family meals/week (10.53±5.70SD vs. 12.88±4.59SD) than White mothers. Low-AL mothers also had more family meals/week in less healthy locations (i.e„ in front of TV, fast food restaurants, cars; 6.80±5.54SD vs. 2.96±2.84SD and 2.97±3.41SD) and fewer meals at the table (2.62±2.71SD vs. 5.69±1.54SD and 5.08±2.29SD) than Whites and high-AL mothers. Low-AL mothers tended to have less access to healthy physical activity and more access to unhealthy meal environments. These findings indicate important characteristics to address when tailoring nutrition education interventions aiming to improve aspects of the home environments of low-AL Hispanic mothers.
