JF  - Native Russian Environment & its Influence on the Behavior & Health of Young Children
PB  - University of California, San Francisco
AB  - The purpose of this descriptive, cross-sectional study was to describe characteristics of the child's environment including family interaction characteristics, parenting style, mothers' worry and how they predict child behavior and health outcomes in Russian families with young children, aged 4-7 years, living in Saint Petersburg, Russia. The goals of this study were establishing foundational data for the improvement of health care and the development of family nursing care in the Russian health system, describing parenting, family and child behavior and health outcomes to guide health care and teaching in both Russia and the United States, and establishing normative data for provision of health care to Russian families who have immigrated to the United States.Guided by the 'developmental niche' model, data from 109 Russian mothers were gathered on the study variables using the McMaster Family Assessment Device, Parenting Style and Dimension Questionnaire, Russian Mothers' Stress Questionnaire, Child Behavior Checklist, and Vulnerable Child Scale. Results from multiple regression indicated that all variables in combination contribute significantly to predict child behavior outcomes. Russian mothers worry regarding negative life events emerged most frequently as a significant predictor in child behavior. This result suggested that as mothers' worry about negative life events increased then child behavior problems increased in total, externalizing and internalizing behavior. The relationship was strongest with internalizing behavior.Russian parents tend to use an authoritative parenting style most often. There was not a significant relationship between mothers' parenting style and child behavior. However when the mothers' perceive that the fathers are using a greater degree of authoritative parenting then child total and internalizing behavior problems decrease.Parenting style, family interaction characteristics, and mothers' worry collectively had a significant impact on child health vulnerability in this sample. Family interaction characteristics was the only significant unique contributor to this model thus as the family interacted more healthfully then the child's vulnerability for health problems was lower.
